The Ekiti Council of Elders has described as unwarranted, the death of two persons, following the recent protest sparked by the government’s restriction on the celebration of Ogun Onire Festival in Ire-Ekiti, Oye local government area of the state. In his appeal, the elder statesman asked the youth to refrain from violent acts and brigandage over the government’s directive to halt the spread of COVID-19 in the state. An attempt by Onire of Ire-Ekiti, Oba Victor Bobade, to enforce the government’s order against mass gathering, due to Coronavirus outbreak, by counselling  Ogun adherents to have a low key celebration, resulted in violent crises, where two persons lost their lives. Vehicles within the premises of Oba Bobade’s palace were vandalised and set ablazed by some irate youths and Ogun worshippers, while protesting against the decision they consider uncustomary. Governor Kayode Fayemi had, a couple of weeks ago, banned the celebration of traditional festivals, pending when the COVID-19 pandemic will subside. Reacting to the killing, on Saturday, in a statement jointly signed by its president, Prof Joseph Oluwasanmi, and secretary, Niyi Ajibulu, the council appealed that the youth should show understanding and adhere to government’s directive. “Ekiti Council is shocked over the violence at Ire-Ekiti during the celebration of Ogun festival. It regrets the loss of lives and destruction of property, and also sympathise with Oba Victor Bobade and the entire community. “Ire Ekiti town is known all over the world for peaceful Ogun celebration annually; a ceremony that is fast becoming a global event, and which stakeholders are striving to turn into a big tourist attraction. “The council urges the government and our leaders to always show understanding of our youth exuberance. The youth must understand that it is the government and traditional institution’s responsibilities to prevent communicable diseases from assuming endemic proportions.”  